@table @manref
@item inet(4)
The @manpage{inet(4)} driver is a classical @dfn{STREAMS} over @dfn{Sockets} approach.  Transport
Provider Interface, @manref{tpi(7)}, Streams are interworked into a socket opened within the driver.
This approach has some serious disadvantages, one of them being speed.

@item udp2(4)
The @manpage{udp2(4)} driver is a second-generation @dfn{STREAMS} UPD driver.  This driver is mostly
a @dfn{STREAMS} implementation and only relies on the @cite{Linux} IP layer for operation.  No
socket is opened internal to the kernel.  This driver performs much faster than the @dfn{STREAMS}
over @dfn{Sockets} approach and rivals the native @dfn{Sockets} implemented under @cite{Linux} in
terms of performance.  This driver is well tested with the test-udp test case executable.

@item rawip2(4)
The @manpage{rawip2(4)} driver is a second-generation @dfn{STREAMS} raw IP driver.  It is similar to
the second-generation UDP driver.  This driver is well tested with the test-rawip test case
executable.

@item tcp2(4)
The @manpage{tcp2(4)} driver is a placeholder for a second-generation @dfn{STREAMS} TCP driver.

@end table

The @cite{@value{PACKAGE_TITLE}} package includes kernel modules, @cite{SVR 4.2} @dfn{STREAMS}
drivers, modules, libraries, utilities, test programs, daemons, and development environment for the
development and execution of @cite{Internet Protocols (INET)} protocol stack components and
applications for the @cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS} environment.

This distribution is only currently applicable to @cite{Linux} 2.4 and 2.6 kernels and was targeted
at @code{ix86}, @code{x86_64}, @code{ppc} and @code{ppc64} architectures, but should build and
install for other architectures as well.

